{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496376"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1344"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1344"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.01,0.05,0.07,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111075"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1344"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93196"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2633"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45134"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111075"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasing abdominal girth and weight gain. Prior to this, his weight had been steady and his diet has not changed. He thinks he has gained about 14 kg. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has never smoked and drinks about six beers a night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His cardiovascular examination reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs or added sounds. His jugular venous pressure is not elevated. His respiratory examination is unremarkable with clear lung fields. His abdomen is uniformly distended and shifting dullness is present. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum albumin: 35 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAscitic fluid analysis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 20.2 g/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal protein: 18 g/L (\u003E25)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 120 cells/\u03bcL (\u003C250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 15%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathophysiology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right heart failure","Peritoneal inflammation","Lymphatic obstruction","Protein loss","Portal hypertension"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates the importance of interpreting ascitic fluid analysis in conjunction with clinical features. The serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) is calculated by subtracting the ascitic fluid albumin from the serum albumin. It reflects the oncotic-hydrostatic pressure gradient between the portal circulation and the ascitic fluid. A high SAAG (\u003E11 g/L) indicates that portal pressure exceeds intraperitoneal pressure by a significant margin, which occurs in conditions that increase portal venous pressure or right atrial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) is high at 14.8 g/L (\u003E11) and the ascitic fluid protein is low at 18 g/L. This combination strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Eportal hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E as the underlying mechanism and is characteristic of cirrhotic ascites. The history of significant alcohol intake and gradual onset support this diagnosis. Other causes of portal hypertension such as Budd-Chiari syndrome would show the same pattern but are less common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause a high SAAG due to increased hydrostatic pressure, but typically produces ascitic fluid with high protein content (\u003E25 g/L) due to congestion. The normal cardiovascular examination and absence of peripheral oedema also make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options mentioned are more likely to produce a low SAAG picture:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritoneal inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E from infection or malignancy typically produces an exudative picture with low SAAG (\u003C11 g/L) and high protein (\u003E25 g/L). The normal ascitic white cell count argues against this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphatic obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E typically produces a low SAAG with high protein content due to lymph accumulation. This pattern is seen in conditions like lymphoma or extensive retroperitoneal disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtein loss\u003C/strong\u003E conditions like nephrotic syndrome typically produce ascites with low SAAG and low protein. While the ascitic protein is low here, the normal serum albumin makes this mechanism unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) \u003E11 g/L indicates portal hypertension, most commonly due to cirrhosis.","The combination of high SAAG and low ascitic fluid protein differentiates cirrhotic from cardiac ascites.","Clinical features and biochemistry must be interpreted together when evaluating ascites."],"references":["Aithal GP, Palaniyappan N, China L, et al. Guidelines on the management of ascites in cirrhosis. Gut 2021;70:9-29. Available at: https://gut.bmj.com/content/70/1/9","Cadogen M. Peritoneal fluid analysis. In: Life in the fast lane [online]. Accessed 2025 Jul 22. Available at: https://litfl.com/peritoneal-fluid-analysis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93196"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1344"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93196"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T16:46:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-08T16:47:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111075"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d